# Move.elm — agent move type (the BFS DSL output)

The Elm port of Python's per-move `desc` dict. Where Python
relies on string-typed dicts (`desc["type"] == "extract_absorb"`
etc.), Elm gets a sum type with one variant per move kind:
`ExtractAbsorb | FreePull | Push | Splice | Shift`. Each
variant carries a record of fields specific to that move.

## Status

- **Label:** WORKHORSE.
- **Mirrors:** `python/bfs_solver.py` § the desc dicts
  emitted by `_enumerate_moves` and consumed by
  `describe_move` + `verbs.step_to_primitives`.

## The five variants

- **`ExtractAbsorb`** — peel/pluck/yank/steal a card from
  HELPER, absorb onto a TROUBLE/GROWING target.
- **`FreePull`** — TROUBLE singleton absorbs onto target.
- **`Push`** — TROUBLE 1- or 2-partial pushes onto HELPER
  (or, when the source bucket is GROWING, the engulf
  variant — same desc shape, the bucket route is implicit
  in the producing enumerator).
- **`Splice`** — insert a TROUBLE singleton into a HELPER
  pure/rb run, splitting it cleanly.
- **`Shift`** — peel a HELPER donor card to replace the
  stolen end of a length-3 run; no spawn.

## Bucket label

`SourceBucket = Trouble | Growing` — used by extract_absorb
and free_pull to identify which bucket the absorber was
in. Carried so the verb translator can render the right DSL
verb ("absorb onto trouble" vs "absorb onto growing").

## Verb subtype on extract_absorb

`ExtractVerb = Peel | Pluck | Yank | Steal | SplitOut` —
physical isolation pattern. Distinct from the Move sum type
itself because all five share the `extract_absorb` shape;
they differ only in which spawned pieces qualify as helpers
vs trouble. `SplitOut` (added 2026-04-26) extracts the
interior of a length-3 run; both halves spawn as singleton
TROUBLE fragments. Closes the only extraction gap in the
verb vocabulary.

